<title type="html"><![CDATA[Isolated Warrior 'special effects']]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5507&amp;p=49961#p49961"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />The sinusoidal pattern is probably timed writes to the horizontal scroll register. The MMC3 scanline counter makes it easier: put in the number of the scanlines until the next time X is supposed to change, and the mapper will trigger an IRQ.<br /></div><br />The NES equivalent to the C64's "tech-tech". Much easier to do when you have more than 8 pixels of hardware scroll <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Tearing apart is likewise writes to the scroll register, resetting the VRAM address . You can tell it's using the MMC3 scanline counter because a pattern repeats every 2 scanlines. (This mapper's counter can't trigger on successive lines.)<br /></div><br />The NES equivalent to the C64's FPP (Flexible Pixel Position), which is used to place lines wherever you want them, including repeating them. Once again much easier with more than 8 pixels of hardware scroll.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=325">LocalH</a> — Mon Aug 17, 2009 9:55 pm</p><hr />
